ome characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beynac","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Croatian: from an old pet form of the personal name <i>Benedikt</i> (see   Benedict  ).","French (<b>Bénac</b>): habitational name from any of the places in Ariège and Hautes-Pyrénées named Bénac, from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Benos</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]}]},{"name":"Gaillard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Philippe, Pierre, Andre, Andree, Ketly, Marcel, Mirlande, Monique.","French: nickname from <i>gaillard</i> ‘vigorous, strong’ (ultimately from Celtic <i>galia</i> ‘strength’). This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gailhard</i>, composed of the elements <i>gail</i> ‘powerful, lusty, cheerful’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gailliard","meanings":["French: variant of   Gaillard   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Gaylord","meanings":["Transferred use of a surname, which is a form, altered by folk etymology, of the Old French nickname <i>Gaillard</i> ‘dandy’. It was adopted as a first name from the 19th century, but it now seems to have suffered the same fate as <i>Gay</i> (  see  Gaye  )."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gaillard II de Beynac was born about 1230, in Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France as the son of Gaillard de BEYNAC. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Helene Gratienne. He died after 1274, in Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France."},"et":{"about 1230–Aft 1274":"umbes 1230–pärast 1274","1230–1274":"1230–1274","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1255–1300":"1255–1300","–1310":"–1310","1185–1225":"1185–1225","1225":"1225","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1310":"1310","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","Aft 1274":"pärast 1274","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Beynac, Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1230–Aft 1274":"noin 1230–1274 jälkeen","1230–1274":"1230–1274","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1255–1300":"1255–1300","–1310":"–1310","1185–1225":"1185–1225","1225":"1225","1300":"1300","1255":"1255","1310":"1310","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","Aft 1274":"1274 jälkeen","about 1230":"noin 1230","Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Beynac, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska","Beynac, Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Limoges, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1230–Aft 1274":"environ 1230–après 1274","1230–1274":"1230–1274","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1255–1300":"1255–1300","–1310":"–1310","1185–1225":"1185–1225","1225":"1225","1300":"13